# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: single-sign-on-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] The **Central Authentication Service** (**CAS**) is a single sign-on protocol for the web.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] Its purpose is to permit a user to access multiple applications while providing their credentials (such as user ID and password) only once.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] It also allows web applications to authenticate users without gaining access to a user's security credentials, such as a password.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] The name *CAS* also refers to a software package that implements this protocol.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] The CAS protocol involves at least three parties: a *client* web browser, the web *application* requesting authentication, and the *CAS server*.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] It may also involve a *back-end service*, such as a database server, that does not have its own HTTP interface but communicates with a web application.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] When the client visits an application requiring authentication, the application redirects it to CAS.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] CAS validates the client's authenticity, usually by checking a username and password against a database (such as Kerberos, LDAP or Active Directory).
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] If the authentication succeeds, CAS returns the client to the application, passing along a service ticket.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] The application then validates the ticket by contacting CAS over a secure connection and providing its own service identifier and the ticket.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] CAS then gives the application trusted information about whether a particular user has successfully authenticated.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] CAS allows multi-tier authentication via proxy address.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] A cooperating *back-end* service, like a database or mail server, can participate in CAS, validating the authenticity of users via information it receives from web applications.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] Thus, a webmail client and a webmail server can all implement CAS.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] CAS was conceived and developed by Shawn Bayern of Yale University Technology and Planning.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] It was later maintained by Drew Mazurek at Yale.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] CAS 2.0 introduced multi-tier proxy authentication.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] Several other CAS distributions have been developed with new features.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] In December 2004, CAS became a project of the Java in Administration Special Interest Group (JASIG), which is as of 2008 responsible for its maintenance and development.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] Formerly called "Yale CAS", CAS is now also known as "Jasig CAS".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] In 2010, Jasig entered into talks with the Sakai Foundation to merge the two organizations.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] The two organizations were consolidated as Apereo Foundation in December 2012.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] Mellon Foundation awarded Yale its First Annual Mellon Award for Technology Collaboration, in the amount of $50,000, for Yale's development of CAS.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] At the time of that award CAS was in use at "hundreds of university campuses (among other beneficiaries)".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/central-authentication-service] In April 2013, CAS Protocol specification 3.0 was released.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] An **identity provider** (abbreviated **IdP**, **IDP**, or **idp**) is a system entity that creates, maintains, and manages identity information for principals and also provides authentication services to relying applications within a federation or distributed network.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] Identity providers offer user authentication as a service.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] Relying party applications, such as web applications, outsource the user authentication step to a trusted identity provider.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] Such a relying party application is said to be *federated*, that is, it consumes federated identity.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] An identity provider is “a trusted provider that lets you use single sign-on (SSO) to access other websites.” SSO enhances usability by reducing password fatigue.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] It also provides better security by decreasing the potential attack surface.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] Identity providers can facilitate connections between cloud computing resources and users, thus decreasing the need for users to re-authenticate when using mobile and roaming applications.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] OpenID Connect (OIDC) is an identity layer on top of OAuth.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] In the domain model associated with OIDC, an identity provider is a special type of OAuth 2.0 authorization server.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] Specifically, a system entity called an OpenID Provider issues JSON-formatted identity tokens to OIDC relying parties via a RESTful HTTP API.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] The Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is a set of profiles for exchanging authentication and authorization data across security domains.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] In the SAML domain model, an identity provider is a special type of authentication authority.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] Specifically, a SAML identity provider is a system entity that issues authentication assertions in conjunction with an SSO profile of SAML.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/identity-provider] A relying party that consumes these authentication assertions is called a SAML service provider.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] IWA is also known by several names like *HTTP Negotiate authentication*, *NT Authentication*, *NTLM Authentication*, *Domain authentication*, *Windows Integrated Authentication*, *Windows NT Challenge/Response authentication*, or simply *Windows Authentication*.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Integrated Windows Authentication uses the security features of Windows clients and servers.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Unlike Basic Authentication or Digest Authentication, initially, it does not prompt users for a user name and password.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] The current Windows user information on the client computer is supplied by the web browser through a cryptographic exchange involving hashing with the Web server.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] If the authentication exchange initially fails to identify the user, the web browser will prompt the user for a Windows user account user name and password.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Integrated Windows Authentication itself is not a standard or an authentication protocol.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] When IWA is selected as an option of a program (e.g. within the *Directory Security* tab of the IIS site properties dialog) this implies that underlying security mechanisms should be used in a preferential order.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] If the Kerberos provider is functional and a Kerberos ticket can be obtained for the target, and any associated settings permit Kerberos authentication to occur (e.g.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Intranet sites settings in Internet Explorer), the Kerberos 5 protocol will be attempted.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Otherwise NTLMSSP authentication is attempted.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Similarly, if Kerberos authentication is attempted, yet it fails, then NTLMSSP is attempted.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] IWA uses SPNEGO to allow initiators and acceptors to negotiate either Kerberos or NTLMSSP.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Third party utilities have extended the Integrated Windows Authentication paradigm to UNIX, Linux and Mac systems.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Integrated Windows Authentication works with most modern web browsers, but does not work over some HTTP proxy servers.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Therefore, it is best for use in intranets where all the clients are within a single domain.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] It may work with other web browsers if they have been configured to pass the user's logon credentials to the server that is requesting authentication.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Where a proxy itself requires NTLM authentication, some applications like Java may not work because the protocol is not described in RFC-2069 for proxy authentication.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] iOS natively supports Kerberos via Kerberos Single Sign-on extension.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Configuring the extension enables Safari and Edge to use Kerberos.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/integrated-windows-authentication] Android has SPNEGO support in Chrome which is adding Kerberos support with a solution like Hypergate Authenticator.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Kerberos builds on symmetric-key cryptography and requires a trusted third party, and optionally may use public-key cryptography during certain phases of authentication.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The protocol was named after the character *Cerberus*, also spelled *Kerberos*, from Greek mythology, the ferocious three-headed guard dog of Hades.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) developed Kerberos in 1988 to protect network services provided by Project Athena.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Its first version was primarily designed by Steve Miller and Clifford Neuman based on the earlier Needham–Schroeder symmetric-key protocol.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Kerberos versions 1 through 3 were experimental and not released outside of MIT.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Kerberos version 4, the first public version, was released on January 24, 1989.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Since Kerberos 4 was developed in the United States, and since it used the Data Encryption Standard (DES) encryption algorithm, U.S. export control restrictions prevented it from being exported to other countries.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] MIT created an exportable version of Kerberos 4 with all encryption code removed, called "Bones".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Eric Young of Australia's Bond University reimplemented DES into Bones, in a version called "eBones", which could be freely used in any country.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Sweden's Royal Institute of Technology released another reimplementation called KTH-KRB.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Neuman and John Kohl published version 5 in 1993 with the intention of overcoming existing limitations and security problems.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Version 5 appeared as RFC 1510, which was then made obsolete by RFC 4120 in 2005.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] In 2005, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) Kerberos working group updated specifications.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] MIT makes an implementation of Kerberos freely available, under copyright permissions similar to those used for BSD.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] In 2007, MIT formed the Kerberos Consortium to foster continued development.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Founding sponsors include vendors such as Oracle, Apple Inc., Google, Microsoft, Centrify Corporation and TeamF1 Inc., and academic institutions such as the Royal Institute of Technology in Sweden, Stanford University, MIT, and vendors such as CyberSafe offering commercially supported versions.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The client authenticates itself to the **Authentication Server (AS)** which is part of the **key distribution center** **(KDC)**.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The KDC issues a **ticket-granting ticket (TGT)**, which is time stamped and encrypts it using the **ticket-granting service's (TGS)** secret key and returns the encrypted result to the user's workstation.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] This is done infrequently, typically at user logon; the TGT expires at some point although it may be transparently renewed by the user's session manager while they are logged in.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] When the client needs to communicate with a service on another node (a "principal", in Kerberos parlance), the client sends the TGT to the TGS, which is another component of the KDC and usually shares the same host as the authentication server.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The service must have already been registered with the TGS with a **Service Principal Name (SPN)**.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The client uses the SPN to request access to this service.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] After verifying that the TGT is valid and that the user is permitted to access the requested service, the TGS issues a **service ticket (ST)** and session keys to the client.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The client then sends the ticket to the **service server (SS)** along with its service request.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The protocol is described in detail below.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The client transforms the password into a symmetric key using a one-way hash or standard key derivation function, depending on the cipher suite used.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] In modern Kerberos (v5), the client often uses this key to encrypt a current timestamp.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] This encrypted timestamp is sent to the AS along with the username as "pre-authentication" to prove the user knows the password before the AS issues any tickets, preventing offline brute-force attacks.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The AS checks to see whether the client is in its database.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Once the client receives messages A and B, it attempts to decrypt message A with the secret key generated from the password entered by the user.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] If the user entered password does not match the password in the AS database, the client's secret key will be different and thus unable to decrypt message A.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] With a valid password and secret key the client decrypts message A to obtain the *Client/TGS Session Key*.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] This session key is used for further communications with the TGS.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] (Note: The client cannot decrypt Message B, as it is encrypted using TGS's secret key.) At this point, the client has enough information to authenticate itself to the TGS.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Upon receiving messages C and D, the TGS retrieves message B out of message C.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] It decrypts message B using the TGS secret key.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] This gives it the *Client/TGS Session Key* and the client ID (both are in the TGT).
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The SS decrypts the ticket (message E) using its own secret key to retrieve the *Client/Server Session Key*.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The client decrypts the confirmation (message H) using the *Client/Server Session Key* and checks whether the timestamp is correct.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] If so, then the client can trust the server and can start issuing service requests to the server.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The server provides the requested services to the client.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Windows 2000 and later versions use Kerberos as their default authentication method.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Some Microsoft additions to the Kerberos suite of protocols are documented in RFC 3244 "Microsoft Windows 2000 Kerberos Change Password and Set Password Protocols".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] RFC 4757 documents Microsoft's use of the RC4 cipher.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] While Microsoft uses and extends the Kerberos protocol, it does not use the MIT software.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Kerberos is used as the preferred authentication method: in general, joining a client to a Windows domain means enabling Kerberos as the default protocol for authentications from that client to services in the Windows domain and all domains with trust relationships to that domain.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] In contrast, when either client or server or both are not joined to a domain (or not part of the same trusted domain environment), Windows will instead use NTLM for authentication between client and server.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Internet web applications can enforce Kerberos as an authentication method for domain-joined clients by using APIs provided under SSPI.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Microsoft Windows and Windows Server include setspn, a command-line utility that can be used to read, modify, or delete the Service Principal Names (SPN) for an Active Directory service account.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Many Unix-like operating systems, including FreeBSD, Apple's macOS, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Oracle's Solaris, IBM's AIX, HP-UX and others, include software for Kerberos authentication of users or services.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] A variety of non-Unix like operating systems such as z/OS, IBM i and OpenVMS also feature Kerberos support.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Embedded implementation of the Kerberos V authentication protocol for client agents and network services running on embedded platforms is also available from companies.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] The Data Encryption Standard (DES) cipher can be used in combination with Kerberos, but is no longer an Internet standard because it is weak.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/kerberos-protocol] Security vulnerabilities exist in products that implement legacy versions of Kerberos which lack support for newer encryption ciphers like AES.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Generally, the OAuth protocol provides a way for resource owners to provide a client application with secure delegated access to server resources.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] It specifies a process for resource owners to authorize third-party access to their server resources without providing credentials.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Designed specifically to work with Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), OAuth essentially allows access tokens to be issued to third-party clients by an authorization server, with the approval of the resource owner.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The third party then uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the resource server.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth began in November 2006 when Blaine Cook was developing an OpenID implementation for Twitter.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Meanwhile, Ma.gnolia needed a solution to allow its members with OpenIDs to authorize Mac OS X Dashboard widgets to access their service.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Cook, Chris Messina and Larry Halff from Magnolia met with David Recordon to discuss using OpenID with the Twitter and Magnolia APIs to delegate authentication.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] They concluded that there were no open standards for API access delegation.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The OAuth discussion group was created in April 2007, for a small group of implementers to write the draft proposal for an open protocol.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] DeWitt Clinton from Google learned of the OAuth project, and expressed his interest in supporting the effort.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] In July 2007, the team drafted an initial specification.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Eran Hammer joined and coordinated the many OAuth contributions creating a more formal specification.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] On 3 October 2007, the OAuth Core 1.0 final draft was released.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] At the 73rd Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meeting in Minneapolis in November 2008, an OAuth BoF was held to discuss bringing the protocol into the IETF for further standardization work.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The event was well attended and there was wide support for formally chartering an OAuth working group within the IETF.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The OAuth 1.0 protocol was published as RFC 5849, an informational Request for Comments, in April 2010.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Since 31 August 2010, all third party Twitter applications have been required to use OAuth.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The OAuth 2.0 framework was published considering additional use cases and extensibility requirements gathered from the wider IETF community.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Albeit being built on the OAuth 1.0 deployment experience, OAuth 2.0 is not backwards compatible with OAuth 1.0.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth 2.0 was published as RFC 6749 and the Bearer Token Usage specification as RFC 6750, both standards track Requests for Comments, in October 2012.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] As of November 2024, the OAuth 2.1 Authorization Framework draft is a work in progress.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] It consolidates the functionality in RFCs OAuth 2.0, OAuth 2.0 for Native Apps, Proof Key for Code Exchange, OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Apps, OAuth Security Best Current, and Bearer Token Usage.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] On 23 April 2009, a session fixation security flaw in the 1.0 protocol was announced.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] It affects the OAuth authorization flow (also known as "3-legged OAuth") in OAuth Core 1.0 Section 6.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Version 1.0a of the OAuth Core protocol was issued to address this issue.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] In January 2013, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a threat model for OAuth 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Among the threats outlined is one called "Open Redirector"; in early 2014, a variant of this was described under the name "Covert Redirect" by Wang Jing.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth 2.0 has been analyzed using formal web protocol analysis.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] This analysis revealed that in setups with multiple authorization servers, one of which is behaving maliciously, clients can become confused about the authorization server to use and may forward secrets to the malicious authorization server (AS Mix-Up Attack).
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] This prompted the creation of a new best current practice internet draft that sets out to define a new security standard for OAuth 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Assuming a fix against the AS Mix-Up Attack in place, the security of OAuth 2.0 has been proven under strong attacker models using formal analysis.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] One implementation of OAuth 2.0 with numerous security flaws has been exposed.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] In April and May 2017, about one million users of Gmail (less than 0.1% of users as of May 2017) were targeted by an OAuth-based phishing attack, receiving an email purporting to be from a colleague, employer or friend wanting to share a document on Google Docs.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Those who clicked on the link within the email were directed to sign in and allow a potentially malicious third-party program called "Google Apps" to access their "email account, contacts and online documents".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Within "approximately one hour", the phishing attack was stopped by Google, who advised those who had given "Google Apps" access to their email to revoke such access and change their passwords.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] In the draft of OAuth 2.1 the use of the PKCE (RFC 7636) extension for native apps has been recommended to all kinds of OAuth clients, including web applications and other confidential clients in order to prevent malicious browser extensions from performing OAuth 2.0 code injection attacks.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth framework specifies several grant types for different use cases.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Facebook's Graph API only supports OAuth 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Google supports OAuth 2.0 as the recommended authorization mechanism for all of its APIs.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Microsoft also supports OAuth 2.0 for various APIs and its Azure Active Directory service, which is used to secure many Microsoft and third party APIs.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth can be used as an authorizing mechanism to access secured RSS/Atom feeds.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Access to RSS/ATOM feeds that require authentication has always been an issue.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] For example, an RSS feed from a secured Google Site could not have been accessed using Google Reader.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Instead, three-legged OAuth would have been used to authorize that RSS client to access the feed from the Google Site.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Free software client implementations of the OAuth2 protocol such as the LibreOffice OAuth2OOo extension allows access to remote resources (ie: via the Google API or the Microsoft Graph API and OAuth 2.0) and possibly even with the LibreOffice Basic language.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] This makes it very easy to write and use HTTP requests supporting the OAuth 2.0 protocol in LibreOffice macros.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth is a service that is complementary to and distinct from OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth is unrelated to OATH, which is a reference architecture for authentication, not a standard for authorization.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] However, OAuth is directly related to OpenID Connect (OIDC), since OIDC is an authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth is also unrelated to XACML, which is an authorization policy standard.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth can be used in conjunction with XACML, where OAuth is used for ownership consent and access delegation whereas XACML is used to define the authorization policies (e.g., managers can view documents in their region).
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth is an *authorization* protocol, rather than an *authentication* protocol.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Using OAuth on its own as an authentication method may be referred to as pseudo-authentication.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The following diagrams highlight the differences between using OpenID (specifically designed as an authentication protocol) and OAuth for authorization.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The site sees that the user is not authenticated.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] It formulates a request for the identity provider, encodes it, and sends it to the user as part of a redirect URL.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Once the identity provider is satisfied that the user is sufficiently authenticated, it processes the application's request, formulates a response, and sends that back to the user along with a redirect URL back to the application.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The application decodes the identity provider's response, and carries on accordingly.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] (OAuth only) The response includes an access token which the application can use to gain direct access to the identity provider's services on the user's behalf.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] The access token acts as a kind of "valet key" that the application can include with its requests to the identity provider, which prove that it has permission from the user to access those APIs.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Because the identity provider typically (but not always) authenticates the user as part of the process of granting an OAuth access token, it is tempting to view a successful OAuth access token request as an authentication method itself.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] However, because OAuth was not designed with this use case in mind, making this assumption can lead to major security flaws.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] XACML is a policy-based, attribute-based access control authorization framework.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth does not provide a policy language with which to define access control policies.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] XACML can be used for its policy language.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Where OAuth focuses on delegated access (I, the user, grant Twitter access to my Facebook wall), and identity-centric authorization, XACML takes an attribute-based approach which can consider attributes of the user, the action, the resource, and the context (who, what, where, when, how).
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] XACML provides more fine-grained access control than OAuth does.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth is limited in granularity to the coarse functionality (the scopes) exposed by the target service.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] As a result, it often makes sense to combine OAuth and XACML together where OAuth will provide the delegated access use case and consent management and XACML will provide the authorization policies that work on the applications, processes, and data.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Lastly, XACML can work transparently across multiple stacks (APIs, web SSO, ESBs, home-grown apps, databases...).
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] OAuth focuses exclusively on HTTP-based apps.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Eran Hammer resigned from his role of lead author for the OAuth 2.0 project, withdrew from the IETF working group, and removed his name from the specification in July 2012.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Hammer cited a conflict between web and enterprise cultures as his reason for leaving, noting that IETF is a community that is "all about enterprise use cases" and "not capable of simple".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] "What is now offered is a blueprint for an authorization protocol", he noted, "that is the enterprise way", providing a "whole new frontier to sell consulting services and integration solutions".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] In comparing OAuth 2.0 with OAuth 1.0, Hammer points out that it has become "more complex, less interoperable, less useful, more incomplete, and most importantly, less secure".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] He explains how architectural changes for 2.0 unbound tokens from clients, removed all signatures and cryptography at a protocol level and added expiring tokens (because tokens could not be revoked) while complicating the processing of authorization.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] David Recordon later also removed his name from the specifications for unspecified reasons.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] Dick Hardt took over the editor role, and the framework was published in October 2012.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/oauth] David Harris, author of the email client Pegasus Mail, has criticised OAuth 2.0 as "an absolute dog's breakfast", requiring developers to write custom modules specific to each service (Gmail, Microsoft Mail services, etc.), and to register specifically with them.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] True single sign-on allows the user to log in once and access services without re-entering authentication factors.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] It should not be confused with same-sign on (Directory Server Authentication), often accomplished by using the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) and stored LDAP databases on (directory) servers.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] A simple version of single sign-on can be achieved over IP networks using cookies but only if the sites share a common DNS parent domain.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Conversely, **single sign-off** or **single log-out** (**SLO**) is the property whereby a single action of signing out terminates access to multiple software systems.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] As different applications and resources support different authentication mechanisms, single sign-on must internally store the credentials used for initial authentication and translate them to the credentials required for the different mechanisms.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Other shared authentication schemes, such as OpenID and OpenID Connect, offer other services that may require users to make choices during a sign-on to a resource, but can be configured for single sign-on if those other services (such as user consent) are disabled.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] An increasing number of federated social logons, like Facebook Connect, do require the user to enter consent choices upon first registration with a new resource, and so are not always single sign-on in the strictest sense.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] SSO shares centralized authentication servers that all other applications and systems use for authentication purposes and combines this with techniques to ensure that users do not have to actively enter their credentials more than once.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] The term *reduced sign-on* (RSO) has been used by some to reflect the fact that *single sign-on* is impractical in addressing the need for different levels of secure access in the enterprise, and as such more than one authentication server may be necessary.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] As single sign-on provides access to many resources once the user is initially authenticated ("keys to the castle"), it increases the negative impact in case the credentials are available to other people and misused.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Therefore, single sign-on requires an increased focus on the protection of the user credentials, and should ideally be combined with strong authentication methods like smart cards and one-time password tokens.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Single sign-on also increases dependence on highly-available authentication systems; a loss of their availability can result in denial of access to all systems unified under the SSO.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] SSO can be configured with session failover capabilities in order to maintain the system operation.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Nonetheless, the risk of system failure may make single sign-on undesirable for systems to which access must be guaranteed at all times, such as security or plant-floor systems.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Furthermore, the use of single-sign-on techniques utilizing social networking services such as Facebook may render third party websites unusable within libraries, schools, or workplaces that block social media sites for productivity reasons.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] It can also cause difficulties in countries with active censorship regimes, such as China and its "Golden Shield Project", where the third party website may not be actively censored, but is effectively blocked if a user's social login is blocked.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] In March 2012, a research paper reported an extensive study on the security of social login mechanisms.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] The authors found 8 serious logic flaws in high-profile ID providers and relying party websites, such as OpenID (including Google ID and PayPal Access), Facebook, Janrain, Freelancer, FarmVille, and Sears.com.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Because the researchers informed ID providers and relying party websites prior to public announcement of the discovery of the flaws, the vulnerabilities were corrected, and no security breaches have been reported.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] In May 2014, a vulnerability named Covert Redirect was disclosed.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] It was first reported "Covert Redirect Vulnerability Related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" by its discoverer Wang Jing, a Mathematical PhD student from Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] In fact, almost all Single sign-on protocols are affected.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Covert Redirect takes advantage of third-party clients susceptible to cross-site scripting (XSS) or open redirect.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] In December 2020, flaws in federated authentication systems were discovered to have been utilized by attackers during the 2020 United States federal government data breach.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Another security issue is that if the session used for SSO is stolen (which can be protected with the HttpOnly cookie flag unlike the SSO token), the attacker can access all the websites that are using the SSO system.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] As originally implemented in Kerberos and SAML, single sign-on did not give users any choices about releasing their personal information to each new resource that the user visited.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] This worked well enough within a single enterprise, like MIT where Kerberos was invented, or major corporations where all of the resources were internal sites.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] However, as federated services like Active Directory Federation Services proliferated, the user's private information was sent out to affiliated sites not under control of the enterprise that collected the data from the user.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Since privacy regulations are now tightening with legislation like the GDPR, the newer methods like OpenID Connect have started to become more attractive; for example MIT, the originator of Kerberos, now supports OpenID Connect.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Single sign-on in theory can work without revealing identifying information such as email addresses to the relying party (credential consumer), but many credential providers do not allow users to configure what information is passed on to the credential consumer.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] As of 2019, Google and Facebook sign-in do not require users to share email addresses with the credential consumer.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] "Sign in with Apple" introduced in iOS 13 allows a user to request a unique relay email address each time the user signs up for a new service, thus reducing the likelihood of account linking by the credential consumer.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Windows environment - Windows login fetches TGT.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Active Directory-aware applications fetch service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Unix/Linux environment - Login via Kerberos PAM modules fetches TGT.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Kerberized client applications such as Evolution, Firefox, and SVN use service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Mobile environment - Apple added native Kerberos support in IOS 13.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] On Android a Mobile Device Management service can add support for Kerberos.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Initial sign-on prompts the user for the smart card.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Additional software applications also use the smart card, without prompting the user to re-enter credentials.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Smart-card-based single sign-on can either use certificates or passwords stored on the smart card.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is an XML-based method for exchanging user security information between an SAML identity provider and a SAML service provider.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] SAML 2.0 supports W3C XML encryption and service-provider–initiated web browser single sign-on exchanges.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] A user wielding a user agent (usually a web browser) is called the subject in SAML-based single sign-on.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] The user requests a web resource protected by a SAML service provider.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the user, issues an authentication request to a SAML identity provider through the user agent.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] The identity provider is the one that provides the user credentials.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] The service provider trusts the user information from the identity provider to provide access to its services or resources.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] A newer variation of single-sign-on authentication has been developed using mobile devices as access credentials.
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] A mobile device is "something you have", as opposed to a password which is "something you know", or biometrics (fingerprint, retinal scan, facial recognition, etc.) which is "something you are".
[src:single-sign-on-deep/single-sign-on] Security experts recommend using at least two out of these three factors (multi-factor authentication) for best protection.
